---
import StyleguideLayout from './_layout/StyleguideLayout.astro';
import SGSwitcher from './_components/SGSwitcher.astro';
import { SmartLink, SmallCaps, highlight as Highlight } from '@components/mdx/index';
import WrappedTable from '@components/mdx/WrappedTable.astro';
import { InlineFootnotes } from '@components/layout/index';
import { Content as ChecklistContent } from './_snippets/checklist.mdx';
import { Content as ListDensityContent } from './_snippets/list-density.mdx';
import { Content as FootnotesContent } from './_snippets/footnotes.mdx';

const toc = [
  { id: 'inline', label: 'Inline elements' },
  { id: 'manual-inline', label: 'Manual inline' },
  { id: 'default-behaviours', label: 'Default behaviours' },
  { id: 'block', label: 'Block-level elements' },
  { id: 'headings', label: 'Headings' },
  { id: 'composite', label: 'Composite sample' },
  { id: 'lists', label: 'Lists' },
  { id: 'tables', label: 'Tables' },
  { id: 'footnotes', label: 'Footnotes' },
  { id: 'realistic', label: 'Realistic example' },
];
---

<StyleguideLayout
  title="Prose & Typography"
  description="Everything you get from writing plain markdown and HTML"
  current="typography"
  toc={toc}
>
  <header>
    <p>
      The <a href="/styleguide/foundations#font-families">foundations section</a> covers the fundamentals
      of typography and spacing. This section demonstrates how content is styled and rendered in various
      contexts. It's a reference for the inline and block-level elements I use on this site.
    </p>
  </header>
  <section id="inline" class="flow">
    <h2>Inline elements</h2>
    <p>Here's how inline text elements are styled...</p>

    <SGSwitcher>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Element</th>
            <th>You write</th>
            <th>Renders</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="4">Links</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Link (internal)</td>
            <td><code>[Notes](/notes/)</code></td>
            <td><SmartLink href="/notes/">Notes</SmartLink></td>
            <td
              >Unvisited links are rendered in the accent colour while visited ones are rendered in
              purple. Hover and active behaviour depends on the context. In longform prose on wide
              viewports, coloured underlines are shown instead of coloured text.</td
            >
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Link (external)</td>
            <td><code>[GitHub](https://github.com)</code></td>
            <td><SmartLink href="https://github.com">GitHub</SmartLink></td>
            <td
              >Markdown links are automatically converted to SmartLink components. Those pointing to
              external domains get a small arrow and appropriate attributes.</td
            >
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Raw anchor</td>
            <td><code>&lt;a href="/notes/"&gt;Notes&lt;/a&gt;</code></td>
            <td><a href="/notes/">Notes</a></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="4">Emphasis & weight</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Emphasis</td>
            <td><code>*emphasis*</code></td>
            <td><em>emphasis</em></td>
            <td>Em elements nested inside other em elements are rendered upright.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Strong</td>
            <td><code>**strong**</code></td>
            <td><strong>strong</strong></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Italic</td>
            <td><code>&lt;i&gt;italic&lt;/i&gt;</code></td>
            <td><i>italic</i></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Bold</td>
            <td><code>&lt;b&gt;bold&lt;/b&gt;</code></td>
            <td><b>bold</b></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="4">Code & technical</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Inline code</td>
            <td><code>`code`</code></td>
            <td><code>code</code></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Keyboard</td>
            <td><code>&lt;kbd&gt;Ctrl&lt;/kbd&gt;</code></td>
            <td><kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>S</kbd></td>
            <td>Keyboard input renders as little buttons which depress on hover</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Variable</td>
            <td><code>&lt;var&gt;x&lt;/var&gt;</code></td>
            <td>f(<var>x</var>) = <var>x</var><sup>2</sup></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Sample output</td>
            <td><code>&lt;samp&gt;Build complete&lt;/samp&gt;</code></td>
            <td><samp>Build complete</samp></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Subscript</td>
            <td><code>H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O</code></td>
            <td>H<sub>2</sub>O</td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Superscript</td>
            <td><code>E = mc&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;</code></td>
            <td>E = mc<sup>2</sup></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="4">Edits & highlights</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Marked / highlighted</td>
            <td><code>&lt;mark&gt;highlighted&lt;/mark&gt;</code></td>
            <td><mark>highlighted</mark></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Deleted</td>
            <td><code>~~deleted~~</code></td>
            <td><del>deleted</del></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Strikethrough</td>
            <td><code>&lt;s&gt;struck&lt;/s&gt;</code></td>
            <td><s>struck</s></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="4">References & meta</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Abbreviation</td>
            <td><code>&lt;abbr title="…"&gt;W3C&lt;/abbr&gt;</code></td>
            <td><abbr title="World Wide Web Consortium">W3C</abbr></td>
            <td
              >Abbreviations are rendered in small caps. If a title is present, they're underlined.</td
            >
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Definition</td>
            <td><code>&lt;dfn&gt;design token&lt;/dfn&gt;</code></td>
            <td><dfn>design token</dfn></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Citation</td>
            <td><code>&lt;cite&gt;Title&lt;/cite&gt;</code></td>
            <td><cite>The Elements of Typographic Style</cite></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Inline quote</td>
            <td><code>&lt;q&gt;quote&lt;/q&gt;</code></td>
            <td><q>Typography exists to honor content.</q></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Small print</td>
            <td><code>&lt;small&gt;fine print&lt;/small&gt;</code></td>
            <td><small>fine print</small></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="manual-inline">Manual inline components</h3>
    <p>
      The following inline Astro components are available for use in MDX files or other Astro pages.
    </p>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Component</th>
            <th>You write</th>
            <th>Renders</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>SmallCaps</td>
            <td><code>&lt;SmallCaps&gt;Small Caps&lt;/SmallCaps&gt;</code></td>
            <td><SmallCaps>Small Caps</SmallCaps></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Highlight</td>
            <td><code>&lt;Highlight&gt;highlighted&lt;/Highlight&gt;</code></td>
            <td><Highlight>highlighted</Highlight></td>
            <td><!-- shares .highlight styling with <mark> --></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </SGSwitcher>
  </section>

  <section id="block" class="flow">
    <h2>Block-level elements</h2>
    <p>And here's how the basic block-level elements are styled...</p>

    <h3 id="headings">Headings</h3>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <h1>Heading level 1</h1>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
      <h2>Heading level 2</h2>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
      <h3>Heading level 3</h3>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
      <h4>Heading level 4</h4>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
      <h5>Heading level 5</h5>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
      <h6>Heading level 6</h6>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="paragraphs">Paragraphs</h3>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <p>
        A paragraph of body copy, with <em>emphasis</em>, <strong>strong importance</strong>, a bit
        of <code>inline code</code> and a <SmartLink href="/notes/">link</SmartLink> woven through it.
        Nostrud in deserunt et laborum id adipisicing laboris sint. Consectetur laborum consequat mollit
        laborum.
      </p>
      <p>
        A second paragraph, so the spacing and rhythm between blocks is visible. Nostrud in deserunt
        et laborum id adipisicing laboris sint. Consectetur laborum consequat mollit laborum. Dolore
        occaecat ex anim reprehenderit aliqua. Veniam commodo qui quis anim consectetur pariatur.
        Dolore exercitation esse et. Minim dolor aliquip laboris Lorem nostrud minim incididunt
        fugiat voluptate ex veniam. Nisi aliqua ut veniam incididunt officia cillum aliqua
        reprehenderit velit et mollit eu voluptate. Sunt ut elit ipsum aute duis minim incididunt et
        nulla dolor magna. Officia consequat ex duis.
      </p>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="blockquote">Blockquote</h3>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          A plain markdown blockquote. This is what a single <code>&gt;</code> prefix produces — a
          <code>blockquote</code> wrapping one or more paragraphs.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="hr">Horizontal rule</h3>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
      <hr />
      <p>
        Elit est aliqua excepteur aliquip pariatur voluptate officia Lorem tempor occaecat
        consectetur nisi aliquip est.
      </p>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="composite">Composite sample</h3>
    <p>Here are a few more realistic examples of all these components in action together.</p>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <h2>A section heading</h2>
      <p>
        An opening paragraph that introduces the section, with an <em>emphasised phrase</em> and a
        <SmartLink href="/notes/">link</SmartLink> to set the scene. Dolore occaecat ex anim reprehenderit
        aliqua. Veniam commodo qui quis anim consectetur pariatur. Dolore exercitation esse et. Minim
        dolor aliquip laboris Lorem nostrud minim incididunt fugiat voluptate ex veniam. Nisi aliqua ut
        veniam incididunt officia cillum aliqua reprehenderit velit et mollit eu voluptate. Sunt ut elit
        ipsum aute duis minim incididunt et nulla dolor magna. Officia consequat ex duis.
      </p>
      <h3>A subsection</h3>
      <p>
        Body copy under a subsection heading, showing how headings and paragraphs sit together with
        the right vertical rhythm. Nisi aliqua ut veniam incididunt officia cillum aliqua
        reprehenderit velit et mollit eu voluptate. Sunt ut elit ipsum aute duis minim incididunt et
        nulla dolor magna. Officia consequat ex duis.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>A quotation that breaks up the flow and carries a little extra weight.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>A closing paragraph before a thematic break.</p>
      <hr />
      <p>And a final paragraph after the rule.</p>
    </SGSwitcher>
  </section>

  <section id="lists" class="flow">
    <h2>Lists</h2>
    <p>
      Unordered and ordered lists share much of their styling, and handle nesting properly. Ordered
      lists are rendered with numerals by default and use letters then roman numerals for nested
      items.
    </p>
    <h3 id="lists-unordered">Unordered lists</h3>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <ul>
        <li>A first item</li>
        <li>
          A second item with <em>emphasis</em> and a <SmartLink href="/notes/">link</SmartLink>
        </li>
        <li>
          A third item with nested children
          <ul>
            <li>A nested item</li>
            <li>Another nested item</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>A fourth item</li>
      </ul>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="lists-ordered">Ordered lists</h3>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — markdown `1.`, including nesting. -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <ol>
        <li>The first step</li>
        <li>The second step</li>
        <li>
          The third step, with sub-steps
          <ol>
            <li>
              A sub-step
              <ol>
                <li>A sub-sub-step</li>
                <li>Another sub-sub-step</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Another sub-step</li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li>The fourth step</li>
      </ol>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="lists-checklists">Checklists</h3>
    <p>GFM task lists are supported by default and render as checklists.</p>
    <SGSwitcher>
      <ChecklistContent />
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="lists-density">List density</h3>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — `.long-list-items` is added by the rehype-list-density plugin when items run long. Rendered from a real MDX snippet. -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <ListDensityContent />
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="list-reset">.list-reset</h3>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro. NOTE: Foundations also carries a .list-reset demo (ported in Phase 1) — decide which page should own it. -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: var(--space-m);">
        <div>
          <strong>Without .list-reset</strong>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Writing</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <strong>With .list-reset</strong>
          <ul class="list-reset">
            <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Writing</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </SGSwitcher>
  </section>

  <section id="tables" class="flow">
    <h2>Tables</h2>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro. -->

    <h3 id="tables-basic">Basic table</h3>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — caption, thead, th/td. -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <table>
        <caption>Quarterly results</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Quarter</th>
            <th>Revenue</th>
            <th>Expenses</th>
            <th>Profit</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th>Q1</th>
            <td>$124,500</td>
            <td>$98,200</td>
            <td>$26,300</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Q2</th>
            <td>$156,800</td>
            <td>$112,400</td>
            <td>$44,400</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Q3</th>
            <td>$189,200</td>
            <td>$134,600</td>
            <td>$54,600</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="tables-mixed">Mixed-content cells</h3>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — cells holding code, formatted text and other inline elements. -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Property</th>
            <th>Value</th>
            <th>Description</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>font-size</code></td>
            <td><code>var(--font-size-base)</code></td>
            <td>Base text size for body copy</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>line-height</code></td>
            <td><code>var(--leading-normal)</code></td>
            <td>Comfortable reading rhythm for <em>most</em> text</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>letter-spacing</code></td>
            <td><code>var(--tracking-normal)</code></td>
            <td>Default tracking for body text</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </SGSwitcher>

    <h3 id="tables-wide">Wide / scrolling tables</h3>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — tables wider than their container get a focusable scroll region (div.table-scroll). In MDX this wrapper is automatic via MDX_COMPONENT_REMAPPING; elsewhere use <WrappedTable> (or write the wrapper by hand). -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <WrappedTable>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Quarter</th>
            <th>Revenue</th>
            <th>Expenses</th>
            <th>Profit</th>
            <th>Customers</th>
            <th>Retention</th>
            <th>NPS</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Q1</td>
            <td>$124,500</td>
            <td>$98,200</td>
            <td>$26,300</td>
            <td>1,204</td>
            <td>92%</td>
            <td>54</td>
            <td>Steady growth driven by inbound leads.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Q2</td>
            <td>$156,800</td>
            <td>$112,400</td>
            <td>$44,400</td>
            <td>1,488</td>
            <td>94%</td>
            <td>61</td>
            <td>Launched the new pricing tiers mid-quarter.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Q3</td>
            <td>$189,200</td>
            <td>$134,600</td>
            <td>$54,600</td>
            <td>1,712</td>
            <td>93%</td>
            <td>58</td>
            <td>Slight churn uptick after the pricing change.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </WrappedTable>
    </SGSwitcher>
  </section>

  <section id="footnotes" class="flow">
    <h2>Footnotes</h2>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — footnotes are generated from markdown ([^label] reference, [^label]: definition). Three parts work together: the reference marker, the inline popup (progressive enhancement via InlineFootnotes), and the footnotes section at the bottom. Shown once (not context-switched) so footnote anchor IDs stay unique. -->
    <div class="sg-panel">
      <FootnotesContent />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="realistic" class="flow">
    <h2>Realistic example</h2>
    <!-- TODO(Danny): intro — a longer, realistic passage combining many of the elements above. -->
    <SGSwitcher>
      <h2>The craft of small decisions</h2>
      <p>
        Good design rarely announces itself. It shows up in the <em>accumulation</em> of small choices
        — the <strong>weight of a heading</strong>, the rhythm between paragraphs, the moment a <SmartLink
          href="/notes/">link</SmartLink
        > invites you somewhere new. None of it is loud, and that's the point.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>The details are not the details. They make the design.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <h3>Where it adds up</h3>
      <p>A few places those small decisions compound:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Setting type that's comfortable to read for more than a paragraph</li>
        <li>Keeping <code>inline code</code> legible without breaking the line</li>
        <li>Letting lists and tables carry structure the prose can't</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Press <kbd>Cmd</kbd> + <kbd>P</kbd> to print this and the type still holds together. That resilience<sup
          >1</sup
        > is the result of decisions made long before anyone reads a word.
      </p>
      <hr />
      <p>
        <small
          >A closing aside, set smaller, the way fine print or a postscript might sit at the end of
          a piece.</small
        >
      </p>
    </SGSwitcher>
  </section>

  <InlineFootnotes />
</StyleguideLayout>

<style>
  /* Extra breathing room above each section's main heading. */
  section > h2 {
    margin-block-start: var(--space-xl);
  }
</style>
